The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 A critically-injured man, lying unattended in front of the emergency ward of Medical College and Hospital since Saturday, died on Monday evening. Local residents alleged that the man had come to the emergency ward for treatment on Saturday, but doctors refused to treat him because of the stench emanating from the wounds.

 he man, too weak to walk, lay down under a porch in front of the building. He then reportedly developed gangrene and died. The hospital authorities declared the man ?brought dead? and sent the body for post-mortem. Bhaskar Sinha, secretary of the NGO Swajan, said his organisation would write to health minister Surjya Kanta Mishra and draw his attention to the matter.

 A pandal in Dum Dum was destroyed by a fire on Monday night. The idols were, however, intact. Three tenders were pressed into service and the blaze was controlled in an hour. Fire officials said the cause of the fire was under investigation. A complaint has been lodged with Dum Dum police station against the organisers, Shree Byayam Mandir, for not taking adequate fire-safety measures. Sources said the fire originated from a decorative item in the pandal, on Harsha Nath Mukherjee Road. 

 Medical Bank, a social welfare organisation, on Tuesday took a group of AIDS patients and their children for pandal-hopping in the city. The group included 10 women and six children. 

 Indian Airlines is serving ?the best? of Bengali cuisine to its passengers from October 10-12, as part of the autumn festivities. On the ground, more floorwalkers will be deployed and more counters will be opened to expedite baggage and passenger check-in.

 Two persons, both motorcyclists, were injured in separate accidents on Monday night. Around 1 am, Khokon Dutta Gupta?s vehicle skidded off the road, in front of a factory on Taratala Road, and rammed into a building. He was admitted to SSKM Hospital in a serious condition. 

 he other mishap occurred on Jawaharlal Nehru Road around 2 am. Gobindo Sanyal lost control of his vehicle and rammed into the divider. He, too, was admitted to SSKM Hospital.

 A former columnist with Anandabazar Patrika, Shibdas Banerjee, 78, died on Tuesday after a cardiac arrest at a central Calcutta restaurant. He is survived by his wife, son and daughter. Banerjee also worked for Amrita Bazar Patrika, The Statesman and The Times of India. 

 Kalu Das, 45, a home guard, died after being run over by a private bus on Tollygunge Circular Road on Monday night. Das, on duty at Mahabirtala, sustained injuries in the head. He was a resident of Behala.

 Kesto Hajra, a CSTC conductor, committed suicide by jumping on the rail tracks in front of an approaching train at the Convent Bridge crossing, in Entally, on Tuesday morning. Hajra, 40, was a resident of Gobindo Khatik Road, under Entally police station. 

 Leader of the Opposition in the Calcutta Municipal Corporation, Javed Ahmed Khan, alleged on Tuesday that unlike previous years, water was not being supplied around 5 am during the Ramazan month. Chief engineer (water supply) Dibyendu Roychowdhury denied the allegation, but did not rule out the possibility of problems in a few localities.

